The defendant Parnell D Brown was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Remove Anti-Theft Device (>$500 - $5000), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(f).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Parnell D Brown in court with attorney Louis E. Epps.  Defendant Parnell D Brown in custody.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeds.  Statements made by the state, defense counsel and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant sentenced to serve 1 YEAR at the HOUSE OF CORRECTION, straight time. Credit for 52 days time served. 

COURT STAYS sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for a period of 2 years under the supervision of the Department of Corrections.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION: 
* Comply with the standard rules of probation.
* SERVE 6 MONTHS "condition time" with release privileges for the Day Reporting Center only.
* No contact with the victims, Walmart and Boston Store at Mayfair Mall.
* Cooperate and participate with a mental health evaluation and follow any recommended treatment.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample (unless previously done) and PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Court ordered the Dosage Probation Program.
* Property being held on inventory in reference to this matter is to be returned to the victim, Walmart.
* Defendant is to be assigned to the mental health unit if deemed appropriate by the Probation Department.
* Restitution is set at ZERO.

Defendant Parnell D Brown in court with attorney Louis E. Epps.  Defendant Parnell D Brown in custody.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms or body armor. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
